Problem Statement

You are given a tree with n nodes rooted at node 1. Each node has a color.
A set of nodes is "beautiful" if:
1. All nodes in the set have different colors.
2. For any pair of nodes (u, v), either u is the ancestor of v or v is the ancestor of u. (Meaning the set exists on a single direct path from an ancestor to a descendant).

You are given q queries consisting of a node s.
The answer to each query is the maximum size of a beautiful set that can be formed by selecting nodes strictly from the subtree rooted at s.
Find the sum of answers to all queries modulo 10^9+7.
(Node 1 parent is 0).

Constraints
1 <= N, Q <= 10^5 (implied by typical Hard bounds, though omitted in prompt snippet)

